<div type="definition">
<p>LACK WATER INSIDE OR ON the SURFACE.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The common general term for dryness is zào 燥 (ant. shī 濕 "wet").</p>
<p>2. Gǎo 槁 and kū 枯 (ant. rùn 潤 "lush") are common words referring specifically to dryness of trees and sometimes other plants.</p>
<p>3. Hé/hào 涸 (ant. mǎn 滿 "full of water") views dryness as the result of a process of dissication.</p>
<p>4. Gān 乾 (ant. shī 濕 "wet") focusses on the striking and complete absence of liquid.</p>
<p>5. Jié 渴 merely emphasises insufficient water supply or exhaustion of water supplies.</p>
<p>6. Jiāo 焦 adds to the notion of dryness that of exceesive heat.</p>
<p>CHECK THESE THINGS AGAIN!</p>
        </div>
